We are currently seeking a Resource Biologist for the Missouri River region of South Dakota, which encompasses 20 counties in central South Dakota. The ideal location for this position to work from is the Ft. Pierre Game, Fish and Parks District Office. Job duties include, but aren't limited to, coordinating, assisting with, conducting, monitoring, and reviewing terrestrial wildlife surveys, aerial waterfowl surveys, wildlife research, rule development, habitat management recommendations, wildlife disease management, and data analysis. This position is supervised by the Regional Program Manager.
Duties also involve frequent traveling, often on bad roads and in inclement weather in remote, rural areas; walking long distances in rough country; operating all-terrain vehicles and 4x4 trucks in rough country or around sloughs and in remote areas; handling wildlife, dead and alive, and being exposed to disease and injury; working around domestic livestock; working with all of the hazards associated with aerial wildlife surveys; working in the dark during early morning and late night hours while wildlife are out; answering and returning phone calls in the field.
Licenses and Certifications:
A valid driver license is required.
The successful candidate will also be required to complete an approved ATV and UTV safety course and obtain a South Dakota Department of Agriculture Commercial Applicators license with certifications in category 12 (rodenticide). Additional certifications preferred, but are not required; include prescribed fire training or minimum Fire Fighter Type 2 certification.
NCRC: If you possess a National Career Readiness Certificate, please submit the certificate with your application. For more information on how to acquire a National Career Readiness Certificate contact a South Dakota Department of Labor and Regulation Job Service Office. A certificate is not necessary to be considered.
Successful applicant(s) will be required to undergo a background investigation. An arrest/conviction record will not necessarily bar employment. Successful applicant(s) will undergo an abuse and neglect screening. Offers of employment are conditional upon successful completion of a drug screening.
The Ideal Candidate Will Have:
A bachelor's degree in fisheries, wildlife, ecology, forestry, conservation or equivalent degree and/or experience is preferred.
Knowledge of:
animal behavior, wildlife identification and habitat typically related to species in central South Dakota;
animal diseases and safe-handling practices, disease sampling, collection and preservation methods;
farm and ranch practices of the area and how they affect local wildlife populations;
animal tracking and telemetry procedures;
wildlife management practices and survey techniques;
geographic information system (GIS) software including ArcMap, Survey123, ArcGIS Online, and Collector.
Skill to:
work effectively with agency staff, producers, members of the public, and conservation organizations;
communicate with private landowners;
operate equipment associated with work conditions, such as 4x4 trucks, ATVs, UTVs, trailers, and other necessary equipment;
operate computers, tablets, cell phones, GPS units, and other devices;
publically speak at presentations or events for agency staff or local conservation organizations.
Ability to:
plan and effectively organize work priorities and requests for services;
establish and maintain working relationships with individuals, the general public, local government officials, other state agencies, federal and tribal government officials;
read, interpret, and implement applicable department, state, and federal laws and regulations;
balance landowner, agency, and public's expectations for wildlife populations with factual information and education;
navigate in rural and remote areas, prepare and adapt to changing weather;
use a computer and Microsoft Office programs such as Excel, Access, Word, PowerPoint;
operate 4x4 trucks, all-terrain vehicles, snowmobiles, boats; and repair and service equipment in the field;
communicate information clearly and concisely;
maintain a clean and organized work area.
Additional Requirements: To be considered, attach your responses to the questions below. Your responses must be clear, concise, and numbered.
Please describe in detail your experience conducting aerial wildlife surveys.
Please describe in detail your experience using radio-telemetry.
VETERANS' PREFERENCE ELIGIBLE
The State of South Dakota offers paid employee health insurance plus ten paid holidays, generous vacation leave accrual, and medical, dental, vision, and other benefits. For more information visit http://bhr.sd.gov/workforus/workbenefits.aspx. This position is a member of Class A retirement under SDRS.

